Pods:
Node A: Application deployed in the single pod container.

Node -> Pod -> Container -> app
To extend the availability of the same application we need a one more pod.

Node -> pod a -> container -> app & pod b -> container -> app
Instead of creating a multiple containers in the same pod, we can run multiple pods.

In some scenario, within the same pod, helper container is required to analyze the documents uploaded by the user in the web app container.
Multi container pods concept came in to the picture now.

Docker: 
Need to run an web app & helper app multiple times. Also need to map which web app is linked to which helper app. To delete the web app and helper 
app required different request based on the mapping. 

So, pods can have web app & helper app in the single pod with multi container and deleting also easy to do it. 


# kubectl run nginx --image nginx (to run the nginx application in the pod also to pull nginx images from the docker hub)
# kubectl get pods (to list out the pods created in the cluster)

